  ‚Äñ We can choose any nonzero entry in $C_{k:m,k:m}$ as the
    pivot. ‚¶â
  ¬∂ ‚¶ä
    ‚Äñ Suppose we pick pivot $C_{st} ‚â† 0$ for $k ‚â§ s, t ‚â§ m$. ‚¶â

    ‚Äñ Define $\tilde{C}$ by swapping row $s$ of $C$ with row
      $k$ of $C$ and column $t$ of $C$ with column $k$ of $C$. ‚¶â

    ‚Äñ Then $\tilde{C}_{kk} = C_{st} ‚â† 0$ and there exists an
      ordinary row reduction for $\tilde{C}$. ‚¶â

    ‚Äñ We call this reduction of $(\tilde{C}, \tilde{d})$ a
      ‚ù¨pivoted row reduction‚ù≠ of $C$ or the ‚ù¨$st$-reduction‚ù≠ of C. ‚¶â
  ‚¶â

  ¬∂ ‚¶ä
    ‚Äñ If all remaining pivots are zero, then there is no viable
      pivot. ‚¶â

    ‚Äñ In this case, at least one variable is free and we do
      not have a unique solution. ‚¶â

    ‚Äñ For convenience, in this case, we still call the system
      an $st$-reduction of itself. ‚¶â
  ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß Definition ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ At step $k$ of ordinary elimination, multiples of row $k$
    are subtracted from rows $k+1, ‚Ä¶, m$ to introduce zeros in
    entry $k$ of the rows. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If we denote the matrix at the beginning of that step by
    $X$, then row $k$ of $X$, column $k$ of $X$ and especially
    the pivot $X_{kk}$ play a role. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Ordinarily, we subtract from every entry in the submatrix
    $X_{k+1:m,k:m}$ the product of a number in row $k$ and a
    number in column $k$, divided by the pivot $X_{kk}$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Generally, however, we can choose as pivot any nonzero entry
    of $X_{k:m,k:m}$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ An $m$-variable system $(A, b)$ is ‚ù¨pivot reducible‚ù≠ (or
    ‚ù¨reducible‚ù≠) if there exists a sequence of systems $S_1, ‚Ä¶,
    S_{m-1}$ so that $S_1$ is a reduction of $(A, b)$ and
    $S_{i}$ is a reduction of $S_{i-1}$ for $i = 1, ‚Ä¶, m-1$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call $S_{m-1}$ the ‚ù¨final reduction‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨reduction‚ù≠) of
    $(A, b)$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ An immediate consequence of our definition is ‚¶â
‚¶â

<statement type='proposition'>
  ‚Äñ All systems are reducible. ‚¶â
</statement>